lp Center and identify the common places you&#39;ll go to change these items.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the bottom of this article, the Liquid Variables used in the Customer Help Center are <a href=\"#vars\">listed</a> for you so that you can go beyond the basic examples provided in this article.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#general\">General Tips</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#header\">Header</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#layout\">Layout</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#index\">The Index Page</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#page\">Articles, Topics, and Search Results</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#qanda\">Community Q&amp;A</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#email\">Email form</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#chat\">Chat form</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#vars\">List of Available Variables in Help Center</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"general\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>General Tips for your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider when customizing your Customer Help Center:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Layout changes are specific to each page, with the exception of the Header and Layout pages - for example, if you want to include a script that runs on every page or set a CSS style element, place it in the <a href=\"#header\">Header</a>. In addition, if you want a header or a footer link to appear on every page, place it in the <a href=\"#layout\">Layout</a> section.</li>\r\n\t<li>You can use a dynamic variable set at the top of your page if you&#39;d like to rewrite a variable later in the page, e.g. {%assign myVariable =&quot;Hello&quot;%} to set it and then {{myVariable}} to output it later in the page.</li>\r\n\t<li>Your changes are live - so you may want to make a copy of your template and preview it to see the results of your changes before you publish them.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"header\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Header Section of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The Header Section of the Advanced Mode Help Center Editor provides you with a central place to manage your Style declarations and scripts. You can also use this area to dynamically change the title of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the header section:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>If you&#39;re using CSS to override a style element that&#39;s set somewhere else in Desk.com, you can use the &quot;!important&quot; suffix to make sure that your change is applied (if you need a good CSS primer, check out the <a href=\"http://www.w3schools.com/css/\">W3C Schools CSS site</a>&nbsp;or the handy Snippets at <a href=\"http://css-tricks.com/snippets/\">CSS Tricks</a>.)</li>\r\n\t<li>You can import external style sheets or scripts in this section</li>\r\n\t<li>You can set page header values in this section</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Adding a border to the .content Class on the #support-main div using the &quot;!important&quot; suffix</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You may want to style an existing element of Desk.com without making a large change. An example of a change that overrides an existing class is to add a border to the Content class on the support-main div, e.g.:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:20px !important;margin-right:20px !important;\">#support-main .content { border: 6px solid #CCC !important; //the !important suffix ensures that our CSS change will be applied }</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Changing the Page Name depending on which Desk.com page is displaying</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You can use the Liquid templating language to change the page dynamically in Desk.com. One way you might choose to change the page is to write a different message in the HTML title of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This example demonstrates how you can add a value to the page title by customizing the html title tag in the Header section of the Desk.com Advanced Mode Customer Help Center editor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The possible values of the <b>page</b> variable are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>page_index</li>\r\n\t<li>page_search_result</li>\r\n\t<li>page_search_topic</li>\r\n\t<li>page_search_article</li>\r\n\t<li>question_new</li>\r\n\t<li>question_pre_create</li>\r\n\t<li>question_show</li>\r\n\t<li>email_new</li>\r\n\t<li>email_pre_create</li>\r\n\t<li>email_submitted</li>\r\n\t<li>chat_new</li>\r\n\t<li>chat_pre_create</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the value of the page variable to create a page-specific layout or write out a specific message, e.g.:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;title&gt;\r\n  {{ site.company_name }} | \r\n  {% if page == &#39;page_index&#39; %}\r\n    Portal\r\n  {% elsif page == &#39;page_search_result&#39; %}\r\n    Search Results\r\n  {% elsif page == &#39;page_topic&#39; %}\r\n    {{ topic.name | clip:40 }}\r\n  {% endif %}\r\n&lt;/title&gt; \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"layout\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Layout Section of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the Layout Section of the Advanced Mode editor to set the general layout of your Desk.com Help Center that appears on every Customer Help Center page. You will most likely use this area to set up the general structure of your page design or manipulate changes that appear on every page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the layout section:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>You can use the layout section to include areas such as a header or footer that you want to repeat on every page - this makes the customization process much faster</li>\r\n\t<li>The default layout section contains the Search and Tweet widgets; if you&#39;d like to customize them, you can do so here.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: providing a link to a specific topic in the sidebar</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have topic information that your customers don&#39;t always use, you can create a specific list topics that appears in the sidebar of your Customer Help Center to share valuable content your customers might have missed; in this case - the contents of a specific topic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use a for loop function in Liquid and some html layout to create this &quot;teaser&quot; in the &quot;support-side&quot; div of the layout section to write out the name and link of the first article in the &quot;Hello World&quot; topic, e.g.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n{%for topic in topics%} \r\n      {% if topic.name == &quot;Hello World&quot;%}\r\n\t\r\n      &lt;h3&gt;\t{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\t{% for article in topic.articles limit:1 %}\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;\r\n\t\t&lt;a href=&quot;{{ article.public_url }}&quot;&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\t{% endfor %}\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n       {% endif %} \r\n{%endfor%} \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"index\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Index Page of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The index page is the &quot;home&quot; page of your Customer Help Center and is the first page displayed.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Index page:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The index page provides your general navigation - you can customize it to provide a dynamically generated list of topics rather than the default table design</li>\r\n\t<li>You can change the layout for the index page while maintaining the overall look and feel of the overall layout</li>\r\n\t<li>The index page contains liquid collections of <strong>topics</strong>; each topic contains a collection of <strong>articles</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: change the default table to topics to a dynamically written out list</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>A common customization to the index page of the Desk.com Customer Help Center is to write out a dynamic list of topics. The default HTML writes out this content as a table; however, you may want to write it out and style it differently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n{%for topic in topics%}\r\n\t&lt;h3&gt;\r\n\t\t{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\t\t{% for article in topic.articles %}\r\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;\r\n\t\t\t&lt;a href=&quot;{{ article.public_url }}&quot;&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\t\t{% endfor %}\r\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n\t{%endfor%}\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"page\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Article, Topic, and Search Results Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The Article, Topic, and Search Results pages are other frequently-visited pages in your Customer Help Center:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The Article page of the Customer Help Center provides the template for any page where an Article is displayed.</li>\r\n\t<li>The Topic page of the Customer Help Center is the template for a list of all the articles in that Topic.</li>\r\n\t<li>The Search Results page provides a list of all the items returned from a dynamic Desk.com search.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the article, topic, and search results pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Using a simple if statement or a case statement, you can provide specialized layout for each Topic page (e.g. the &quot;Welcome&quot; Topic may have a different background graphic than the &quot;Advanced&quot; Topic page</li>\r\n\t<li>If you don&#39;t like the default search result you can change the styling so that items have longer or shorter preview length</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: removing the pagination link on a topic page</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>Desk.com gives you the ability to page between available topics on a topic page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;d like to remove this link and display only some of the topics (in this example, we&#39;re limiting the display to 5, simply make the following changes in the Advanced Mode editor on the Page(Topic) page:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>change {% for article in articles %} to {% for article in topic.articles limit:5 %}</li>\r\n\t<li>remove &lt;div id=&#39;pagination&#39;&gt; {{ more_article_block }} &lt;/div&gt;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: displaying only the first 100 characters of a link</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You can apply a liquid <a href=\"https://github.com/shopify/liquid/wiki/liquid-for-designers\">filter</a> to {{ article.body_text | truncate:100 }}<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"qanda\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Community Q&amp;A Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The Community Question and Answer Pages (Q&amp;A) are displayed when you enable Questions and Answers in a specific topic on your Customer Help Center. Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Q&amp;A pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>You may want to use some CSS styling to highlight a best answer.<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"email\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Email Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Desk.com uses two different kinds of email intake forms in the Customer Help Center - the main one you&#39;re likely to use is the Email form - and you may also choose to use the email widget. Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Email pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>If you&#39;d like to use different email forms, you can customize additional copies of the Email form pages using additional Help Center templates</li>\r\n\t<li>You can use the Email widget to style input from a mobile phone or tablet; you can also use the Email widget to place your Desk.com email form on another site than your Support Help Center.</li>\r\n\t<li>You should consider using the email &quot;Pre-Create&quot; to offer additional options to customers and increase the likelihood that they will help themselves instead of creating a ticket.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Changing the Fields on the Email Form to take First and Last Name</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You may wish to ask for both first and last names when your customers email you - in that case, simply remove the {{interaction_name}} field from your email form and add in the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nfirst: &lt;input class=&quot;default l&quot; id=&quot;customer_first_name&quot; name=&quot;customer[first_name]&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; /&gt;\r\nlast: &lt;input class=&quot;default l&quot; id=&quot;customer_last_name&quot; name=&quot;customer[last_name]&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; /&gt; \r\n</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"chat\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Chat Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>If you enable Chat in Desk.com, there are two sets of pages that you can customize - the individual chat pages and a &quot;Widget&quot; that you can embed elsewhere. Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Chat pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>You can style both the initial chat page and the page that results when you&#39;ve connected to the Desk.com Chat</li>\r\n\t<li>If you&#39;d like to display the Chat link only when Agents are available, you&#39;ll need to use the Chat Widget</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Making a field required on the Chat Form</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>To make a field required, you&#39;ll need to add to the existing jquery statement that&#39;s running in the page. For example, if you wanted the phone number to be required, you could add:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n$(&quot;#interaction_phone&quot;).rules(&quot;add&quot;, { required:true, messages: { required: &quot;! required&quot; }\r\n</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"vars\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h3>Available Variables in the Customer Support Center</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A note on usage: </strong>if you&#39;re using a variable would like to output its value, use the curly brackets to tell the Liquid interpreter to output this variable, e.g. {{home_link}}). If you are using a variable name inside an expression or within another Liquid tag, you don&#39;t need the curly brackets. You can find the list of variables used in the Desk.com Support Center here:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/2916-list-of-liquid-variables\">List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h3><br />\r\nRelated Articles</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/2916-list-of-liquid-variables\">List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"https://github.com/shopify/liquid/wiki/liquid-for-designers\">Liquid for Designers (external link)</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/13891\">Making the Customer Help Center Your Own</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/1547-advanced-portal-template-editting\">Advanced Help Center Template Editing</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n","body_email":"The Advanced Mode Customer Help Center feature in Desk.com gives you great freedom to customize the look and feel of Desk.com using the Liquid templating language (check out this reference for additional information.)\n\nVisit Admin &gt; Support Center &gt; Web Templates to begin customizing your Customer Help Center. You can use CSS and HTML to change the layout and decoration of the page, and you can also use the available Liquid variable to produce dynamic markup and make your customer Help Center pages display the information you'd like to share with customers.\n\nThis article details tips you may want to use throughout your Customer Help Center and also highlights specific changes you may want to make on individual pages within the Customer Help Center. The article is organized by the areas in the Advanced Mode editor to make it easier for you to identify the places where you may want to customize your Customer Help Center and identify the common places you'll go to change these items.\n\nAt the bottom of this article, the Liquid Variables used in the Customer Help Center are listed for you so that you can go beyond the basic examples provided in this article. \r\n\r\n  General Tips \r\n Header \r\n Layout \r\n The Index Page \r\n Articles, Topics, and Search Results \r\n Community Q&amp;A \r\n Email form \r\n Chat form \r\n List of Available Variables in Help Center \r\n  \r\n\r\n General Tips for your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider when customizing your Customer Help Center: \r\n\r\n  Layout changes are specific to each page, with the exception of the Header and Layout pages - for example, if you want to include a script that runs on every page or set a CSS style element, place it in the Header. In addition, if you want a header or a footer link to appear on every page, place it in the Layout section. \r\n You can use a dynamic variable set at the top of your page if you'd like to rewrite a variable later in the page, e.g. {%assign myVariable =\"Hello\"%} to set it and then {{myVariable}} to output it later in the page. \r\n Your changes are live - so you may want to make a copy of your template and preview it to see the results of your changes before you publish them.\n \r\n  back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Header Section of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The Header Section of the Advanced Mode Help Center Editor provides you with a central place to manage your Style declarations and scripts. You can also use this area to dynamically change the title of the page.\n\nHere are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the header section: \r\n\r\n  If you're using CSS to override a style element that's set somewhere else in Desk.com, you can use the \"!important\" suffix to make sure that your change is applied (if you need a good CSS primer, check out the W3C Schools CSS site or the handy Snippets at CSS Tricks.) \r\n You can import external style sheets or scripts in this section \r\n You can set page header values in this section \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: Adding a border to the .content Class on the #support-main div using the \"!important\" suffix \r\n\r\n You may want to style an existing element of Desk.com without making a large change. An example of a change that overrides an existing class is to add a border to the Content class on the support-main div, e.g.: \r\n\r\n #support-main .content { border: 6px solid #CCC !important; //the !important suffix ensures that our CSS change will be applied } \r\n\r\n Example: Changing the Page Name depending on which Desk.com page is displaying \r\n\r\n You can use the Liquid templating language to change the page dynamically in Desk.com. One way you might choose to change the page is to write a different message in the HTML title of the page.\n\nThis example demonstrates how you can add a value to the page title by customizing the html title tag in the Header section of the Desk.com Advanced Mode Customer Help Center editor.\n\nThe possible values of the page variable are as follows: \r\n\r\n  page_index \r\n page_search_result \r\n page_search_topic \r\n page_search_article \r\n question_new \r\n question_pre_create \r\n question_show \r\n email_new \r\n email_pre_create \r\n email_submitted \r\n chat_new \r\n chat_pre_create \r\n  Use the value of the page variable to create a page-specific layout or write out a specific message, e.g.: \r\n\r\n \r\n&lt;title&gt;\r\n  {{ site.company_name }} | \r\n  {% if page == 'page_index' %}\r\n    Portal\r\n  {% elsif page == 'page_search_result' %}\r\n    Search Results\r\n  {% elsif page == 'page_topic' %}\r\n    {{ topic.name | clip:40 }}\r\n  {% endif %}\r\n&lt;/title&gt; \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Layout Section of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n Use the Layout Section of the Advanced Mode editor to set the general layout of your Desk.com Help Center that appears on every Customer Help Center page. You will most likely use this area to set up the general structure of your page design or manipulate changes that appear on every page.\n\nHere are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the layout section: \r\n\r\n  You can use the layout section to include areas such as a header or footer that you want to repeat on every page - this makes the customization process much faster \r\n The default layout section contains the Search and Tweet widgets; if you'd like to customize them, you can do so here. \r\n  Example: providing a link to a specific topic in the sidebar \r\n\r\n If you have topic information that your customers don't always use, you can create a specific list topics that appears in the sidebar of your Customer Help Center to share valuable content your customers might have missed; in this case - the contents of a specific topic.\n\nUse a for loop function in Liquid and some html layout to create this \"teaser\" in the \"support-side\" div of the layout section to write out the name and link of the first article in the \"Hello World\" topic, e.g. \r\n\r\n \r\n{%for topic in topics%} \r\n      {% if topic.name == \"Hello World\"%}\r\n\r\n      &lt;h3&gt;{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n{% for article in topic.articles limit:1 %}\r\n&lt;li&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\"{{ article.public_url }}\"&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;\r\n&lt;/li&gt;\r\n{% endfor %}\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n       {% endif %} \r\n{%endfor%} \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Index Page of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The index page is the \"home\" page of your Customer Help Center and is the first page displayed.\n\nHere are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Index page: \r\n\r\n  The index page provides your general navigation - you can customize it to provide a dynamically generated list of topics rather than the default table design \r\n You can change the layout for the index page while maintaining the overall look and feel of the overall layout \r\n The index page contains liquid collections of topics; each topic contains a collection of articles \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: change the default table to topics to a dynamically written out list \r\n\r\n A common customization to the index page of the Desk.com Customer Help Center is to write out a dynamic list of topics. The default HTML writes out this content as a table; however, you may want to write it out and style it differently.\n\n  \r\n\r\n \r\n{%for topic in topics%}\r\n&lt;h3&gt;\r\n{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n{% for article in topic.articles %}\r\n&lt;li&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\"{{ article.public_url }}\"&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n{% endfor %}\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n{%endfor%}\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Article, Topic, and Search Results Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The Article, Topic, and Search Results pages are other frequently-visited pages in your Customer Help Center: \r\n\r\n  The Article page of the Customer Help Center provides the template for any page where an Article is displayed. \r\n The Topic page of the Customer Help Center is the template for a list of all the articles in that Topic. \r\n The Search Results page provides a list of all the items returned from a dynamic Desk.com search.  \r\n  Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the article, topic, and search results pages: \r\n\r\n  Using a simple if statement or a case statement, you can provide specialized layout for each Topic page (e.g. the \"Welcome\" Topic may have a different background graphic than the \"Advanced\" Topic page \r\n If you don't like the default search result you can change the styling so that items have longer or shorter preview length \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: removing the pagination link on a topic page \r\n\r\n Desk.com gives you the ability to page between available topics on a topic page.\n\nIf you'd like to remove this link and display only some of the topics (in this example, we're limiting the display to 5, simply make the following changes in the Advanced Mode editor on the Page(Topic) page: \r\n\r\n  change {% for article in articles %} to {% for article in topic.articles limit:5 %} \r\n remove &lt;div id='pagination'&gt; {{ more_article_block }} &lt;/div&gt; \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: displaying only the first 100 characters of a link \r\n\r\n You can apply a liquid filter to {{ article.body_text | truncate:100 }}\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Community Q&amp;A Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The Community Question and Answer Pages (Q&amp;A) are displayed when you enable Questions and Answers in a specific topic on your Customer Help Center. Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Q&amp;A pages: \r\n\r\n  You may want to use some CSS styling to highlight a best answer.\n\n \r\n  back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Email Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n Desk.com uses two different kinds of email intake forms in the Customer Help Center - the main one you're likely to use is the Email form - and you may also choose to use the email widget. Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Email pages: \r\n\r\n  If you'd like to use different email forms, you can customize additional copies of the Email form pages using additional Help Center templates \r\n You can use the Email widget to style input from a mobile phone or tablet; you can also use the Email widget to place your Desk.com email form on another site than your Support Help Center. \r\n You should consider using the email \"Pre-Create\" to offer additional options to customers and increase the likelihood that they will help themselves instead of creating a ticket. \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: Changing the Fields on the Email Form to take First and Last Name \r\n\r\n You may wish to ask for both first and last names when your customers email you - in that case, simply remove the {{interaction_name}} field from your email form and add in the following: \r\n\r\n \r\nfirst: &lt;input class=\"default l\" id=\"customer_first_name\" name=\"customer[first_name]\" type=\"text\" /&gt;\r\nlast: &lt;input class=\"default l\" id=\"customer_last_name\" name=\"customer[last_name]\" type=\"text\" /&gt; \r\n \r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Chat Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n If you enable Chat in Desk.com, there are two sets of pages that you can customize - the individual chat pages and a \"Widget\" that you can embed elsewhere. Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Chat pages: \r\n\r\n  You can style both the initial chat page and the page that results when you've connected to the Desk.com Chat \r\n If you'd like to display the Chat link only when Agents are available, you'll need to use the Chat Widget \r\n  Example: Making a field required on the Chat Form \r\n\r\n To make a field required, you'll need to add to the existing jquery statement that's running in the page. For example, if you wanted the phone number to be required, you could add: \r\n\r\n \r\n$(\"#interaction_phone\").rules(\"add\", { required:true, messages: { required: \"! required\" }\r\n \r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Available Variables in the Customer Support Center \r\n\r\n A note on usage: if you're using a variable would like to output its value, use the curly brackets to tell the Liquid interpreter to output this variable, e.g. {{home_link}}). If you are using a variable name inside an expression or within another Liquid tag, you don't need the curly brackets. You can find the list of variables used in the Desk.com Support Center here: List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com.  \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n \nRelated Articles \r\n\r\n  List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com \r\n Liquid for Designers (external link) \r\n Making the Customer Help Center Your Own \r\n Advanced Help Center Template Editing","body_email_auto":true,"body_chat":"The Advanced Mode Customer Help Center feature in Desk.com gives you great freedom to customize the look and feel of Desk.com using the Liquid templating language (check out this reference for additional information.)Visit Admin &gt; Support Center &... http://j.mp/txPoNr","body_chat_auto":true,"body_web_callback":"<a name=\"top\"></a>\r\n\r\n<p>The Advanced Mode Customer Help Center feature in Desk.com gives you great freedom to customize the look and feel of Desk.com using the Liquid templating language (check out <a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/2916-list-of-liquid-variables\">this reference</a> for additional information.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Visit Admin &gt; Support Center &gt; Web Templates to begin customizing your Customer Help Center. You can use CSS and HTML to change the layout and decoration of the page, and you can also use the available Liquid variable to produce dynamic markup and make your customer Help Center pages display the information you&#39;d like to share with customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This article details tips you may want to use throughout your Customer Help Center and also highlights specific changes you may want to make on individual pages within the Customer Help Center. The article is organized by the areas in the Advanced Mode editor to make it easier for you to identify the places where you may want to customize your Customer Help Center and identify the common places you&#39;ll go to change these items.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the bottom of this article, the Liquid Variables used in the Customer Help Center are <a href=\"#vars\">listed</a> for you so that you can go beyond the basic examples provided in this article.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#general\">General Tips</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#header\">Header</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#layout\">Layout</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#index\">The Index Page</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#page\">Articles, Topics, and Search Results</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#qanda\">Community Q&amp;A</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#email\">Email form</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#chat\">Chat form</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"#vars\">List of Available Variables in Help Center</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p><a name=\"general\"></a></p>\r\n\r\n<h4>General Tips for your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider when customizing your Customer Help Center:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Layout changes are specific to each page, with the exception of the Header and Layout pages - for example, if you want to include a script that runs on every page or set a CSS style element, place it in the <a href=\"#header\">Header</a>. In addition, if you want a header or a footer link to appear on every page, place it in the <a href=\"#layout\">Layout</a> section.</li>\r\n\t<li>You can use a dynamic variable set at the top of your page if you&#39;d like to rewrite a variable later in the page, e.g. {%assign myVariable =&quot;Hello&quot;%} to set it and then {{myVariable}} to output it later in the page.</li>\r\n\t<li>Your changes are live - so you may want to make a copy of your template and preview it to see the results of your changes before you publish them.<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"header\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Header Section of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The Header Section of the Advanced Mode Help Center Editor provides you with a central place to manage your Style declarations and scripts. You can also use this area to dynamically change the title of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the header section:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>If you&#39;re using CSS to override a style element that&#39;s set somewhere else in Desk.com, you can use the &quot;!important&quot; suffix to make sure that your change is applied (if you need a good CSS primer, check out the <a href=\"http://www.w3schools.com/css/\">W3C Schools CSS site</a>&nbsp;or the handy Snippets at <a href=\"http://css-tricks.com/snippets/\">CSS Tricks</a>.)</li>\r\n\t<li>You can import external style sheets or scripts in this section</li>\r\n\t<li>You can set page header values in this section</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Adding a border to the .content Class on the #support-main div using the &quot;!important&quot; suffix</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You may want to style an existing element of Desk.com without making a large change. An example of a change that overrides an existing class is to add a border to the Content class on the support-main div, e.g.:</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:20px !important;margin-right:20px !important;\">#support-main .content { border: 6px solid #CCC !important; //the !important suffix ensures that our CSS change will be applied }</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Changing the Page Name depending on which Desk.com page is displaying</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You can use the Liquid templating language to change the page dynamically in Desk.com. One way you might choose to change the page is to write a different message in the HTML title of the page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This example demonstrates how you can add a value to the page title by customizing the html title tag in the Header section of the Desk.com Advanced Mode Customer Help Center editor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The possible values of the <b>page</b> variable are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>page_index</li>\r\n\t<li>page_search_result</li>\r\n\t<li>page_search_topic</li>\r\n\t<li>page_search_article</li>\r\n\t<li>question_new</li>\r\n\t<li>question_pre_create</li>\r\n\t<li>question_show</li>\r\n\t<li>email_new</li>\r\n\t<li>email_pre_create</li>\r\n\t<li>email_submitted</li>\r\n\t<li>chat_new</li>\r\n\t<li>chat_pre_create</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the value of the page variable to create a page-specific layout or write out a specific message, e.g.:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n&lt;title&gt;\r\n  {{ site.company_name }} | \r\n  {% if page == &#39;page_index&#39; %}\r\n    Portal\r\n  {% elsif page == &#39;page_search_result&#39; %}\r\n    Search Results\r\n  {% elsif page == &#39;page_topic&#39; %}\r\n    {{ topic.name | clip:40 }}\r\n  {% endif %}\r\n&lt;/title&gt; \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"layout\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Layout Section of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Use the Layout Section of the Advanced Mode editor to set the general layout of your Desk.com Help Center that appears on every Customer Help Center page. You will most likely use this area to set up the general structure of your page design or manipulate changes that appear on every page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the layout section:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>You can use the layout section to include areas such as a header or footer that you want to repeat on every page - this makes the customization process much faster</li>\r\n\t<li>The default layout section contains the Search and Tweet widgets; if you&#39;d like to customize them, you can do so here.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: providing a link to a specific topic in the sidebar</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>If you have topic information that your customers don&#39;t always use, you can create a specific list topics that appears in the sidebar of your Customer Help Center to share valuable content your customers might have missed; in this case - the contents of a specific topic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use a for loop function in Liquid and some html layout to create this &quot;teaser&quot; in the &quot;support-side&quot; div of the layout section to write out the name and link of the first article in the &quot;Hello World&quot; topic, e.g.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n{%for topic in topics%} \r\n      {% if topic.name == &quot;Hello World&quot;%}\r\n\t\r\n      &lt;h3&gt;\t{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\t{% for article in topic.articles limit:1 %}\r\n\t&lt;li&gt;\r\n\t\t&lt;a href=&quot;{{ article.public_url }}&quot;&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;\r\n\t&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\t{% endfor %}\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n       {% endif %} \r\n{%endfor%} \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"index\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Index Page of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The index page is the &quot;home&quot; page of your Customer Help Center and is the first page displayed.<br />\r\n<br />\r\nHere are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Index page:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The index page provides your general navigation - you can customize it to provide a dynamically generated list of topics rather than the default table design</li>\r\n\t<li>You can change the layout for the index page while maintaining the overall look and feel of the overall layout</li>\r\n\t<li>The index page contains liquid collections of <strong>topics</strong>; each topic contains a collection of <strong>articles</strong></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: change the default table to topics to a dynamically written out list</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>A common customization to the index page of the Desk.com Customer Help Center is to write out a dynamic list of topics. The default HTML writes out this content as a table; however, you may want to write it out and style it differently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n{%for topic in topics%}\r\n\t&lt;h3&gt;\r\n\t\t{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n\t&lt;ul&gt;\r\n\t\t{% for article in topic.articles %}\r\n\t\t&lt;li&gt;\r\n\t\t\t&lt;a href=&quot;{{ article.public_url }}&quot;&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n\t\t{% endfor %}\r\n\t&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n\t{%endfor%}\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"page\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Article, Topic, and Search Results Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The Article, Topic, and Search Results pages are other frequently-visited pages in your Customer Help Center:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>The Article page of the Customer Help Center provides the template for any page where an Article is displayed.</li>\r\n\t<li>The Topic page of the Customer Help Center is the template for a list of all the articles in that Topic.</li>\r\n\t<li>The Search Results page provides a list of all the items returned from a dynamic Desk.com search.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the article, topic, and search results pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>Using a simple if statement or a case statement, you can provide specialized layout for each Topic page (e.g. the &quot;Welcome&quot; Topic may have a different background graphic than the &quot;Advanced&quot; Topic page</li>\r\n\t<li>If you don&#39;t like the default search result you can change the styling so that items have longer or shorter preview length</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: removing the pagination link on a topic page</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>Desk.com gives you the ability to page between available topics on a topic page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;d like to remove this link and display only some of the topics (in this example, we&#39;re limiting the display to 5, simply make the following changes in the Advanced Mode editor on the Page(Topic) page:</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li>change {% for article in articles %} to {% for article in topic.articles limit:5 %}</li>\r\n\t<li>remove &lt;div id=&#39;pagination&#39;&gt; {{ more_article_block }} &lt;/div&gt;</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: displaying only the first 100 characters of a link</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You can apply a liquid <a href=\"https://github.com/shopify/liquid/wiki/liquid-for-designers\">filter</a> to {{ article.body_text | truncate:100 }}<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"qanda\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Community Q&amp;A Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>The Community Question and Answer Pages (Q&amp;A) are displayed when you enable Questions and Answers in a specific topic on your Customer Help Center. Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Q&amp;A pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>You may want to use some CSS styling to highlight a best answer.<br />\r\n\t<br />\r\n\t&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"email\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Email Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>Desk.com uses two different kinds of email intake forms in the Customer Help Center - the main one you&#39;re likely to use is the Email form - and you may also choose to use the email widget. Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Email pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>If you&#39;d like to use different email forms, you can customize additional copies of the Email form pages using additional Help Center templates</li>\r\n\t<li>You can use the Email widget to style input from a mobile phone or tablet; you can also use the Email widget to place your Desk.com email form on another site than your Support Help Center.</li>\r\n\t<li>You should consider using the email &quot;Pre-Create&quot; to offer additional options to customers and increase the likelihood that they will help themselves instead of creating a ticket.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Changing the Fields on the Email Form to take First and Last Name</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>You may wish to ask for both first and last names when your customers email you - in that case, simply remove the {{interaction_name}} field from your email form and add in the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\nfirst: &lt;input class=&quot;default l&quot; id=&quot;customer_first_name&quot; name=&quot;customer[first_name]&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; /&gt;\r\nlast: &lt;input class=&quot;default l&quot; id=&quot;customer_last_name&quot; name=&quot;customer[last_name]&quot; type=&quot;text&quot; /&gt; \r\n</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"chat\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h4>Customizing the Chat Pages of your Customer Help Center</h4>\r\n\r\n<p>If you enable Chat in Desk.com, there are two sets of pages that you can customize - the individual chat pages and a &quot;Widget&quot; that you can embed elsewhere. Here are a few general tips you&#39;ll want to consider for the Chat pages:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li>You can style both the initial chat page and the page that results when you&#39;ve connected to the Desk.com Chat</li>\r\n\t<li>If you&#39;d like to display the Chat link only when Agents are available, you&#39;ll need to use the Chat Widget</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<h5>Example: Making a field required on the Chat Form</h5>\r\n\r\n<p>To make a field required, you&#39;ll need to add to the existing jquery statement that&#39;s running in the page. For example, if you wanted the phone number to be required, you could add:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre>\r\n$(&quot;#interaction_phone&quot;).rules(&quot;add&quot;, { required:true, messages: { required: &quot;! required&quot; }\r\n</pre>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<h5><a href=\"#top\">back to top</a></h5>\r\n<a name=\"vars\"></a>\r\n\r\n<h3>Available Variables in the Customer Support Center</h3>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A note on usage: </strong>if you&#39;re using a variable would like to output its value, use the curly brackets to tell the Liquid interpreter to output this variable, e.g. {{home_link}}). If you are using a variable name inside an expression or within another Liquid tag, you don&#39;t need the curly brackets. You can find the list of variables used in the Desk.com Support Center here:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/2916-list-of-liquid-variables\">List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com</a>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4>&nbsp;</h4>\r\n\r\n<h3><br />\r\nRelated Articles</h3>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/2916-list-of-liquid-variables\">List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"https://github.com/shopify/liquid/wiki/liquid-for-designers\">Liquid for Designers (external link)</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/13891\">Making the Customer Help Center Your Own</a></li>\r\n\t<li><a href=\"http://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/1547-advanced-portal-template-editting\">Advanced Help Center Template Editing</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n","body_web_callback_auto":true,"body_twitter":"The Advanced Mode Customer Help Center feature in Desk.com gives you great freedom to customize the lo... https://support.desk.com/customer/portal/articles/240552-understanding-pages-in-the-customer-support-center","body_twitter_auto":true,"body_qna":"The Advanced Mode Customer Help Center feature in Desk.com gives you great freedom to customize the look and feel of Desk.com using the Liquid templating language (check out this reference for additional information.)\n\nVisit Admin &gt; Support Center &gt; Web Templates to begin customizing your Customer Help Center. You can use CSS and HTML to change the layout and decoration of the page, and you can also use the available Liquid variable to produce dynamic markup and make your customer Help Center pages display the information you'd like to share with customers.\n\nThis article details tips you may want to use throughout your Customer Help Center and also highlights specific changes you may want to make on individual pages within the Customer Help Center. The article is organized by the areas in the Advanced Mode editor to make it easier for you to identify the places where you may want to customize your Customer Help Center and identify the common places you'll go to change these items.\n\nAt the bottom of this article, the Liquid Variables used in the Customer Help Center are listed for you so that you can go beyond the basic examples provided in this article. \r\n\r\n  General Tips \r\n Header \r\n Layout \r\n The Index Page \r\n Articles, Topics, and Search Results \r\n Community Q&amp;A \r\n Email form \r\n Chat form \r\n List of Available Variables in Help Center \r\n  \r\n\r\n General Tips for your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider when customizing your Customer Help Center: \r\n\r\n  Layout changes are specific to each page, with the exception of the Header and Layout pages - for example, if you want to include a script that runs on every page or set a CSS style element, place it in the Header. In addition, if you want a header or a footer link to appear on every page, place it in the Layout section. \r\n You can use a dynamic variable set at the top of your page if you'd like to rewrite a variable later in the page, e.g. {%assign myVariable =\"Hello\"%} to set it and then {{myVariable}} to output it later in the page. \r\n Your changes are live - so you may want to make a copy of your template and preview it to see the results of your changes before you publish them.\n \r\n  back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Header Section of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The Header Section of the Advanced Mode Help Center Editor provides you with a central place to manage your Style declarations and scripts. You can also use this area to dynamically change the title of the page.\n\nHere are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the header section: \r\n\r\n  If you're using CSS to override a style element that's set somewhere else in Desk.com, you can use the \"!important\" suffix to make sure that your change is applied (if you need a good CSS primer, check out the W3C Schools CSS site or the handy Snippets at CSS Tricks.) \r\n You can import external style sheets or scripts in this section \r\n You can set page header values in this section \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: Adding a border to the .content Class on the #support-main div using the \"!important\" suffix \r\n\r\n You may want to style an existing element of Desk.com without making a large change. An example of a change that overrides an existing class is to add a border to the Content class on the support-main div, e.g.: \r\n\r\n #support-main .content { border: 6px solid #CCC !important; //the !important suffix ensures that our CSS change will be applied } \r\n\r\n Example: Changing the Page Name depending on which Desk.com page is displaying \r\n\r\n You can use the Liquid templating language to change the page dynamically in Desk.com. One way you might choose to change the page is to write a different message in the HTML title of the page.\n\nThis example demonstrates how you can add a value to the page title by customizing the html title tag in the Header section of the Desk.com Advanced Mode Customer Help Center editor.\n\nThe possible values of the page variable are as follows: \r\n\r\n  page_index \r\n page_search_result \r\n page_search_topic \r\n page_search_article \r\n question_new \r\n question_pre_create \r\n question_show \r\n email_new \r\n email_pre_create \r\n email_submitted \r\n chat_new \r\n chat_pre_create \r\n  Use the value of the page variable to create a page-specific layout or write out a specific message, e.g.: \r\n\r\n \r\n&lt;title&gt;\r\n  {{ site.company_name }} | \r\n  {% if page == 'page_index' %}\r\n    Portal\r\n  {% elsif page == 'page_search_result' %}\r\n    Search Results\r\n  {% elsif page == 'page_topic' %}\r\n    {{ topic.name | clip:40 }}\r\n  {% endif %}\r\n&lt;/title&gt; \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Layout Section of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n Use the Layout Section of the Advanced Mode editor to set the general layout of your Desk.com Help Center that appears on every Customer Help Center page. You will most likely use this area to set up the general structure of your page design or manipulate changes that appear on every page.\n\nHere are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the layout section: \r\n\r\n  You can use the layout section to include areas such as a header or footer that you want to repeat on every page - this makes the customization process much faster \r\n The default layout section contains the Search and Tweet widgets; if you'd like to customize them, you can do so here. \r\n  Example: providing a link to a specific topic in the sidebar \r\n\r\n If you have topic information that your customers don't always use, you can create a specific list topics that appears in the sidebar of your Customer Help Center to share valuable content your customers might have missed; in this case - the contents of a specific topic.\n\nUse a for loop function in Liquid and some html layout to create this \"teaser\" in the \"support-side\" div of the layout section to write out the name and link of the first article in the \"Hello World\" topic, e.g. \r\n\r\n \r\n{%for topic in topics%} \r\n      {% if topic.name == \"Hello World\"%}\r\n\r\n      &lt;h3&gt;{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n{% for article in topic.articles limit:1 %}\r\n&lt;li&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\"{{ article.public_url }}\"&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;\r\n&lt;/li&gt;\r\n{% endfor %}\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n       {% endif %} \r\n{%endfor%} \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Index Page of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The index page is the \"home\" page of your Customer Help Center and is the first page displayed.\n\nHere are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Index page: \r\n\r\n  The index page provides your general navigation - you can customize it to provide a dynamically generated list of topics rather than the default table design \r\n You can change the layout for the index page while maintaining the overall look and feel of the overall layout \r\n The index page contains liquid collections of topics; each topic contains a collection of articles \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: change the default table to topics to a dynamically written out list \r\n\r\n A common customization to the index page of the Desk.com Customer Help Center is to write out a dynamic list of topics. The default HTML writes out this content as a table; however, you may want to write it out and style it differently.\n\n  \r\n\r\n \r\n{%for topic in topics%}\r\n&lt;h3&gt;\r\n{{topic.name}}&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n{% for article in topic.articles %}\r\n&lt;li&gt;\r\n&lt;a href=\"{{ article.public_url }}\"&gt;{{ article.subject_plain | clip:40 }}&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;\r\n{% endfor %}\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n{%endfor%}\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Article, Topic, and Search Results Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The Article, Topic, and Search Results pages are other frequently-visited pages in your Customer Help Center: \r\n\r\n  The Article page of the Customer Help Center provides the template for any page where an Article is displayed. \r\n The Topic page of the Customer Help Center is the template for a list of all the articles in that Topic. \r\n The Search Results page provides a list of all the items returned from a dynamic Desk.com search.  \r\n  Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the article, topic, and search results pages: \r\n\r\n  Using a simple if statement or a case statement, you can provide specialized layout for each Topic page (e.g. the \"Welcome\" Topic may have a different background graphic than the \"Advanced\" Topic page \r\n If you don't like the default search result you can change the styling so that items have longer or shorter preview length \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: removing the pagination link on a topic page \r\n\r\n Desk.com gives you the ability to page between available topics on a topic page.\n\nIf you'd like to remove this link and display only some of the topics (in this example, we're limiting the display to 5, simply make the following changes in the Advanced Mode editor on the Page(Topic) page: \r\n\r\n  change {% for article in articles %} to {% for article in topic.articles limit:5 %} \r\n remove &lt;div id='pagination'&gt; {{ more_article_block }} &lt;/div&gt; \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: displaying only the first 100 characters of a link \r\n\r\n You can apply a liquid filter to {{ article.body_text | truncate:100 }}\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Community Q&amp;A Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n The Community Question and Answer Pages (Q&amp;A) are displayed when you enable Questions and Answers in a specific topic on your Customer Help Center. Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Q&amp;A pages: \r\n\r\n  You may want to use some CSS styling to highlight a best answer.\n\n \r\n  back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Email Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n Desk.com uses two different kinds of email intake forms in the Customer Help Center - the main one you're likely to use is the Email form - and you may also choose to use the email widget. Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Email pages: \r\n\r\n  If you'd like to use different email forms, you can customize additional copies of the Email form pages using additional Help Center templates \r\n You can use the Email widget to style input from a mobile phone or tablet; you can also use the Email widget to place your Desk.com email form on another site than your Support Help Center. \r\n You should consider using the email \"Pre-Create\" to offer additional options to customers and increase the likelihood that they will help themselves instead of creating a ticket. \r\n    \r\n\r\n Example: Changing the Fields on the Email Form to take First and Last Name \r\n\r\n You may wish to ask for both first and last names when your customers email you - in that case, simply remove the {{interaction_name}} field from your email form and add in the following: \r\n\r\n \r\nfirst: &lt;input class=\"default l\" id=\"customer_first_name\" name=\"customer[first_name]\" type=\"text\" /&gt;\r\nlast: &lt;input class=\"default l\" id=\"customer_last_name\" name=\"customer[last_name]\" type=\"text\" /&gt; \r\n \r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Customizing the Chat Pages of your Customer Help Center \r\n\r\n If you enable Chat in Desk.com, there are two sets of pages that you can customize - the individual chat pages and a \"Widget\" that you can embed elsewhere. Here are a few general tips you'll want to consider for the Chat pages: \r\n\r\n  You can style both the initial chat page and the page that results when you've connected to the Desk.com Chat \r\n If you'd like to display the Chat link only when Agents are available, you'll need to use the Chat Widget \r\n  Example: Making a field required on the Chat Form \r\n\r\n To make a field required, you'll need to add to the existing jquery statement that's running in the page. For example, if you wanted the phone number to be required, you could add: \r\n\r\n \r\n$(\"#interaction_phone\").rules(\"add\", { required:true, messages: { required: \"! required\" }\r\n \r\n \r\n\r\n back to top \r\n\r\n\r\n Available Variables in the Customer Support Center \r\n\r\n A note on usage: if you're using a variable would like to output its value, use the curly brackets to tell the Liquid interpreter to output this variable, e.g. {{home_link}}). If you are using a variable name inside an expression or within another Liquid tag, you don't need the curly brackets. You can find the list of variables used in the Desk.com Support Center here: List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com.  \r\n\r\n   \r\n\r\n \nRelated Articles \r\n\r\n  List of Liquid Variables in Desk.com \